<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-026-184 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 441 536</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIDRANGE Systems  Oct 29 1991 v4 n21 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Professional Press Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM links with supercomputer firm: joint development pact coversmassively parallel supercomputing. (IBM/Thinking Machines Corp.andO;contract) (Brief Article)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Thinking Machines Corp. (Contracts)International Business Machines Corp. (Contracts).andO;Topic:     Parallel ProcessingContractsMarketing AgreementsSupercomputersMainframe ComputersStrategic Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y.andP;  -- IBM recently signed a joint development agreement thatmakes last month's ES/9000 announcements look small from strictly a hardwareperspective.andP;  Big Blue signed with Thinking Machines, a Cambridge,Mass.-based supercomputer developer.andP;  Terms of the deal were not disclosed.andM;According to IBM, the Randamp;D effort will combine Thinking Machine's expertise inmassively parallel supercomputing with IBM's experience in high-performancemainframe systems.andM;Massively parallel supercomputers are comprised of a large number, oftenthousands, of processors that work together to solve a single large-scaleproblem.andP;  Usually such problems require solutions in a short time frame, suchas weather forecasting.andM;Carl Conti, IBM Senior VP and GM of enterprise systems, says that IBMmainframe customers have indicated that massively parallel computing is animportant technology of the future, adding that the alliance between IBM andThinking Machines will result in state-of-the-art parallel FORTRAN andsupercomputers.andM;&quot;This advances supercomputing for everyone,&quot; says Thinking Machines PresidentSheryl Handler.andP;  &quot;Combining with an IBM environment is critical to many ofour customers.andP;  And all of our customers will benefit as we take advantage ofIBM's leadership in semiconductor and disk technologies.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>